Aromatic and medicinal plants, especially those belonging to Lamiaceae and Apiaceae families, have been used for centuries in traditional medicine for the treatment of several pathologies with many therapeutic effects being associated with the presence of volatile compounds, i.e., essential oils. In fact, these compounds have been described as bioactive agents, primarily due to their antifungal, antibacterial and anti-inflammatory properties (
 Cowan, 1999; 
 Zuzarte et al., 2013; 
 Alves-Silva et al., 2016). In many cases, the use of these plants/compounds is based on empiric knowledge. Thus, the spectrum of action as well as the underlying mechanisms of action are lacking and should be deeply explored.
